<br>
But I am tired of, and ultimately will not allow myself to be again bitten by the &quot;their song on the radio is really good, I'll buy the album&quot; only to find out that the one song is the only good one they have. <br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I am not the kind of person who has 1500 MP3's, all against copyright on my computer. If I enjoy a majority of the songs on an album, I support the artist(s) and the company. <br>
<br>
But I view putting out one good radio released song off an album of shitty tracks, as bordering on false and misleading advertising practices. The way you represent the contents of the album should be consistant with the actual songs on that album.<br>
<br>
If I 'try before I buy' and that annoys some record label execs and some artists that can only manage 1 or 2 good songs per record, I say &quot;good, fuck you for putting out trash that you have to basically con people into buying&quot;. <br>
<br>
The only thing MP3s, illegal or not, have done for me, is allow me to be a more informed consumer. If that frightens some record execs and some artists, I'm glad. Perhaps the need to only produce *good* songs and high quality music will drive them to not put out filler on albums.<br>
<br>
If you want to get into the legal semantics, sure, it's not legal. But neither is using programs to damage other people's property; the retributive aspect of laws in North America have to somehow be associated with the crime. If the programs deleted the songs off the person's computer, fine; but if they damage it, it's every bit as wrong as downloading material in the first place.<br>
<br>
I have a very hard time feeling sorry for the record industry, when I want to make an informed choice about what music is good, and what is shit. I don't have the opportunity to make that distinction by any legal and free means; the 'pay to play' philosophy is greedy and every bit as wrong and deceptive as 'stealing' MP3's. <br>
<br>
Making sure the music we are going to buy is actually *good* before we spend our money may well be illegal, but it is no more 'wrong' than record labels that direct which songs will get play time, and which will be ignored. And an unjust law, is no law at all. <br>
<br>
Now, if we could return a CD based on the fact that it's junk, or of low quality, I wouldn't be downloading so much music. <br>
<br>
But so much of what I've found lately, with the exception of a very few indeed, is not worth my money. If I can't find out by listening to it on the radio, I'm sure as hell not going to shell out 20/25 bucks to be disappointed.<br>
<br>
Yers, <p><font color="blue">Roggulbuk Bonesmasher</font><br>
